item.title: Happy family destroyed by ICE
item.description: Renee Good on the left, her wife in the center, her mother on the right. Posing in front of their wedding photos. I'm not going to post a picture of their children. She was a mother of three, a daughter and two sons. "That's my wife, I don't know what to do," her wife is saying in one of the videos showing the murderers. "I have a six-year-old at school... we're new here we don't have anyone. We need a doctor." They had recently moved to Minnesota from Colorado. Her murderers blocked a doctor on the scene from rendering aid, and used their vehicles to block an ambulance called to the scene until local police made them move their trucks. Renee Good was not involved with any protest or resistance movement, was not wanted by the police, and was a citizen. She was just driving after dropping her wife off, having just dropped their kid off at school.

item.title: The cops are not your friend
item.description:
This is for my fellow Americans. I don’t recommend doing this anywhere, but I don’t know the legal protocol in other countries. I saw a Court Cam YouTube compilation of corrupt cops getting busted, one of them being busted for planting evidence at the scene. The victims of the evidence-planting cop said the dangerous line when asked if he could search their vehicle: “I have nothing to hide.” With the police being labeled as swearing to protect and serve, we want to believe that they would do right by us. Unfortunately, that’s not always the case. The police are there to make an arrest, not to protect you. The WORST thing you can do is give the police access to your car, house, or cellphone without a warrant. Just because you have nothing to hide doesn’t mean that the police won’t put something there that you were seen “acting suspiciously about” to justify arresting you. THE COPS ARE NOT YOUR FRIEND. . For those curious about the link: https://youtu.be/Jl2Ay601bAI?si=fNUbiy3aAvzXwdug Here’s a cute video by two verified lawyers talking about what to do when the cops ask to search your vehicle: https://youtube.com/shorts/Q8pCvGXTF30?si=1muFTJ5DoGpApXrh
Cops are under no obligation to be truthful when interviewing you. They can lie to you about evidence they “found” that doesn’t actually exist. They can say that they’re not looking to arrest you when they 100% are. They don’t have to be honest about their answers to your questions. The cops aren’t there to protect your best interest, they’re there to make an arrest. Always talk to a lawyer before you talk to the police! . Here’s a link that goes into much better detail about police lying tactics and how to handle interviews: ttps://www.blasslaw.com/faqs/when-can-the-police-lie-to-you/
